  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Life-saving WASH emergency support for IDPs in Madinatu Camp, Old Maiduguri, Jere LGA</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The severe influx of new arrivals from northern Borno in the already over-congested camp settings of Maiduguri/Jere, including Madinatu camp, requires a timely and effective life-saving WASH response from the humanitarian sector. 
According to the IOM new arrivals tracking sheet for Madinatu, a total of 3,440 individuals (new arrivals) arrived in Madinatu between November 8, 2018 to March 6, 2019. In total, from DTM R25 (5,491 individuals) to March 6, 2019, IOM recorded a total of 8,931 arrivals into Madinatu.  Those new arrivals are in urgent need of basic WASH services. Since WASH facilities of the already existing IDPs are overstretched due to the influx, this population is also in urgent need of additional assistance.  
As part of the 90-Days Emergency Response Plan, this project fills the identified WASH gaps in Madinatu camp for new arrivals and existing (IDP) population. New arrivals and existing (IDP) populations are assessed to be in urgent need of safe water, sanitation facilities and hygiene to prevent outbreaks of water-borne diseases. 
Therefore, new arrivals and the (IDP) population are being supported through the provision of safe water, construction of gender-segregated sanitation facilities and intense hygiene promotion campaigns. Consequently, the project contributes towards reduced mortality rate of most vulnerable people and prepares the population against the outbreak of cholera in advance.</narrative>
  </description>
